      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nIn this chapter, we develop the idea that division reveals something inherent in nature: a process of redistribution without loss. When matter is divided, it does not disappear — it is conserved, as concluded by Antoine Lavoisier (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nHowever, division should not be seen merely as something that separates. In many cases, it is necessary to define groups through divisions before building something. This leads us to the following reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "68227419-2430-4359-b902-f6cf87b8941d",
                     "text": "Holmes, F. L.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1985",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3f68de7c-d729-4b62-9bb1-36c6f518fea4",
                     "text": "History Tracers Editors.",
                     "page": "Simplicity vs. Complexity",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Dividing to Multiply</b><br /><br />Is it easier to build something by moving huge, heavy pieces that you can’t carry?<br /><br />Or is it simpler to build something using pieces that you can carry?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_philosophy",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### First Idea\n\nIn the previous text (<htcite0>), when revisiting the example of the divided leaf, we noticed that there is at least one more element: the center, which is often ignored because our focus tends to be on the edges.\n\nLet’s perform a few more divisions using only one half of the leaf:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3f68de7c-d729-4b62-9bb1-36c6f518fea4",
                     "text": "History Tracers Editors",
                     "page": "Simplicity vs. Complexity",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 1: Cutting...</b><br /><br />1. Take a sheet of paper and cut it into pieces. It’s not necessary to follow the pattern shown in Figure 1.<br /><br />2. Keep cutting until you get tired or until you wish to stop.</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"cutTable\" class=\"tableTen tableTenBgBlue\"><tr><th colspan=\"10\"><i>Shredded leaf</i></th></tr> </table> </p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Visual representation of the cut leaf into 100 pieces.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The Maximum Possible\n\nIn the case of *History Tracers*, we decided to stop the division at 100 small pieces to avoid using too many computer resources when creating the table.\n\nWhen you did the practice, you probably also stopped for some reason.\n\nThis brings us to a question about possible limits:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: The Smallest</b><br /><br />If, for some reason, we can no longer divide a leaf because of our own nature, does that mean the leaf cannot be divided any further?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The First Idea\n\nThe first ideas suggesting that nature might contain something indivisible date back thousands of years. The first to propose this hypothesis is believed to have been Democritus, who was born around <htdate0>.\n\nAccording to his model of indivisible matter, the universe was composed of four fundamental elements: earth, water, air, and fire (<htcite0>).\n\nDemocritus’ initial idea was based on several important points (<htcite1>):\n- Atoms would exist in an “infinite number.” It is important to note that infinity is not a number, but something greater than any quantity (<htcite2>). Therefore, it would be more accurate to say that the number of atoms **tends toward infinity** (<htcite3>).\n- Atoms would have different sizes..\n- They would be solid.\n- There would be no spaces between them.\n\nThis model, containing only four elements and completely solid atoms, is represented in **Figure 1**:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "424fb1ac-867e-4895-8a04-367655e6f1ea",
                     "text": "Stweart, Ken",
                     "page": "Atomic Model",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
